{{wiktionary|evolution}} 
[[File:Term evolution used in 1889.jpeg|thumbnail|The term ''evolution'' in a book published in 1889]]

The English noun '''''evolution''''' (from [[Latin]]  {{lang|la|ēvolūtiō}} "unfolding, unrolling") refers to any kind of accumulation of change, or gradual directional change. It is the 3,117th most commonly used word in English.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evolution|url=http://www.forgottenbooks.com/worddata/evolution|website=Word Data|accessdate=24 October 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117021424/http://www.forgottenbooks.com/worddata/evolution|archivedate=17 November 2015|df=}}</ref>

While the term primarily refers to [[biology|biological]] [[evolution]], there are various types of [[Chemistry|chemical]] evolution and it is also found in economics, historical linguistics, and many other technical fields where [[system]]s develop or change gradually over time, e.g.  [[stellar evolution]], [[cultural evolution]],  the [[evolution of an idea]], [[evolution (philosophy)|metaphysical evolution]], [[spiritual evolution]], etc.

The English term prior to the late 19th century was confined to referring to goal-directed, pre-programmed processes such as [[embryological development]]. A pre-programmed task, as in a military [[:wikt:maneuver|maneuver]], using this definition, may be termed an "evolution."  

The term ''evolution'' (from its literal meaning of "unfolding" of something into its true or explicit form) carries a connotation of gradual improvement or directionality from a beginning to an end point. This contrasts with the more general [[:wikt:development|development]], which can indicate change in any direction, or [[revolution]], which implies recurring, periodic change. The term  [[biological devolution]] is coined as an antonym to ''evolution'', indicating such degeneration or decrease in quality or complexity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evolution|url=http://etymonline.com/index.php?term=evolution&allowed_in_frame=0|website=Online Etymology Dictionary|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref>

